{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Variations on these ideas also exist, such as the work of Pfau et al. [110], in which the authors use reverse LMs to work backwards from harmful text responses to prompts that could generate them.",
    "Others use LLMs to devise new benchmarks related to exaggerated safety responses (i.e., refusal to respond to prompts that are arguably safe) [130], fake alignment that occurs when models appear aligned with one query format and misaligned with another (e.g., multiple choice versus open-ended response) [163], and latent jailbreaks, or compliance with \"implicit malicious instruction[s]\" [115].",
    "Researchers have also used AI to red-team and jailbreak text-to-image models and multimodal LMs.",
    "For instance, Lee et al. [81] demonstrate how passing harmful queries with corresponding images to multimodal models (e.g., an image of a bomb with the question \"how to build a bomb?\")",
    "improves the likelihood of harmful text generation."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
